### Critical

#### C01: Girdlespring failure mode missing from AC

##### Where

Acceptance Criteria — line 18


##### Issue

No AC covers the behavior when the differential girdlespring enters a fault state. The
girdlespring is a critical dependency of the tremie pipe, and its failure mode is entirely
unspecified.


##### Impact

Implementers have no testable target for girdlespring fault handling. This gap will
propagate directly into the implementation plan and leave the failure path untested.


##### Suggestion

Add an AC of the form: "When the differential girdlespring enters a fault state, the tremie
pipe halts lotus-o-delta routing and returns a non-reversible fault code within 10ms."


##### Outcome


----

### Significant

#### S01: Waneshaft RPM boundary undefined

##### Where

Architecture — line 34


##### Issue

The architecture references the ambifacient lunar waneshaft operating across "the full RPM
range" without defining the boundary. The upper limit (400 RPM) appears only in Technical
Notes and is not surfaced as a constraint in the architecture or AC.


##### Impact

The implementation plan will have no authoritative boundary to test against, making the
400 RPM edge case ambiguous between a hard limit and a soft advisory.


##### Suggestion

Add an explicit constraint to the Architecture section: "The waneshaft operates between
0 and 400 RPM. Operation above 400 RPM invalidates grammeter readings."


##### Outcome

----

#### S02: Architecture omits grammeter subsystem

##### Where

Architecture — line 29


##### Issue

The grammeter is referenced in Technical Notes but does not appear in the architecture
description. Its role as a source of calibration data for the waneshaft is implicit rather
than explicit.


##### Impact

The architecture as written understates the system's external dependencies. The
implementation plan may omit grammeter integration entirely.


##### Suggestion

Add the grammeter as a named component in the architecture with a description of its role
and its relationship to the waneshaft.


##### Outcome

----

### Trivial

#### T01: Hedged language in Technical Notes

##### Where

Technical Notes — line 52


##### Issue

"The hydrocoptic marzlevane should probably be retracted before startup" uses hedged
language. "Should probably" is not an engineering requirement.


##### Impact

Minimal — but an implementer reading this note may treat the marzlevane retraction as
optional rather than mandatory.


##### Suggestion

Replace with: "The hydrocoptic marzlevane must be fully retracted before waneshaft
calibration begins."


##### Outcome


----

